[{"sha":"4f24979a0cc5969e03c3c47195b69d9399f8076a","author":{"name":"xiadanni","email":"c2e90d6d1afc98c5af8edc893995c11a5f50c538@huawei.com"},"message":"docker: fix docker kill command block

docker kill command block when executes with start/restart concurrently
script to reproduce it

```
function do_test() {
    local cid
    local pid_list
    local timeout_pid
	opt_list=("restart" "stop" "start" "inspect" "kill")
    cid=$(docker run -itd ubuntu bash)
    for i in $(seq 1 100); do
        pid_list=()
        for opt in ${opt_list[*]}; do
            docker "${opt}" "${cid}" &
            #docker exec "${cid}" ps &
        done
        wait
    done
}
```

When docker kill command execute with start/restart command
concurrently, kill command may block at <-container.Wait.
As s.waitStop is variable, so there is case that waitStop in Wait
function get a new s.waitStop(the old one is already closed before).
So kill command blocked to wait the new s.waitStop close.

docker kill command block when executes with start/restart concurrently
script to reproduce it

`function do_test() {
    local cid
    local pid_list
    local timeout_pid
	opt_list=("restart" "stop" "start" "inspect" "kill")
    cid=$(docker run -itd ubuntu bash)
    for i in $(seq 1 100); do
        pid_list=()
        for opt in ${opt_list[*]}; do
            docker "${opt}" "${cid}" &
            #docker exec "${cid}" ps &
        done
        wait
    done
}`

When docker kill command execute with start/restart command
concurrently, kill command may block at <-container.Wait.
As s.waitStop is variable, so there is case that waitStop in Wait
function get a new s.waitStop(the old one is already closed before).
So kill command blocked to wait the new s.waitStop close.

Change-Id: Iaace4040aa94388965fb17e073c9caadc79d29b7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/d8d85aae446c90007250c466a9cb005d6d3f67bd"},{"sha":"078772e803c7befd06846a2d92a592e9c9f104bc","author":{"name":"Nat Jeffries","email":"2e09a75ee8475320aa1ac5230cf082097d8413be@gmail.com"},"message":"Address review comment","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/078772e803c7befd06846a2d92a592e9c9f104bc"},{"sha":"40e15760e02d3c8afd145f385aae570813336893","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

[{"sha":"cbfd38bd41e91433b7a23348ae65d3adff2bc20b","author":{"name":"Alexander Alekhin","email":"68add3c7f0912f500ebe6e9539930fd1bb229c72@gmail.com"},"message":"core: rework code locality

- to reduce binaries size of FFmpeg Windows wrapper
- MinGW linker doesn't support -ffunction-sections (used for FFmpeg Windows wrapper)
- move code to improve locality with its used dependencies
- move UMat::dot() to matmul.dispatch.cpp (Mat::dot() is already there)
- move UMat::inv() to lapack.cpp
- move UMat::mul() to arithm.cpp
- move UMat:eye() to matrix_operations.cpp (near setIdentity() implementation)
- move normalize(): convert_scale.cpp => norm.cpp
- move convertAndUnrollScalar(): arithm.cpp => copy.cpp
- move scalarToRawData(): array.cpp => copy.cpp
- move transpose(): matrix_operations.cpp => matrix_transform.cpp
- move flip(), rotate(): copy.cpp => matrix_transform.cpp (rotate90 uses flip and transpose)
- add 'OPENCV_CORE_EXCLUDE_C_API' CMake variable to exclude compilation of C-API functions from the core module
- matrix_wrap.cpp: add compile-time checks for CUDA/OpenGL calls
- the steps above allow to reduce FFmpeg wrapper size for ~1.5Mb (initial size of OpenCV part is about 3Mb)

backport is done to improve merge experience (less conflicts)

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

[{"sha":"7368fc8fe76b9c04ce0c622402908139ad2e740a","author":{"name":"Martin Balin","email":"84ffdecb1b029a3e0ae894af0e87a1e5e13ecda9@oracle.com"},"message":"Updates to better document the build of VSCode.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KacerCZ/netbeans/commits/7368fc8fe76b9c04ce0c622402908139ad2e740a"},{"sha":"460042be723b28b430f88c77c1ee7ab18f364892","author":{"name":"Matthias Bläsing","email":"2733b4844ad39354bd21fd2bca55a8804e19a60d@doppel-helix.eu"},"message":"[NETBEANS-5380] Override generated ant projects for MX with NetBeans support

In profiles from repositry updater runs a huge CPU load originating 
from SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl was found. In parallel excessive runtimes
for project scanning were observed.

Comparing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl and SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation
the latter has an aggressive caching system, which results in much less
cpu usage. Just removing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl is not a solution, as
it is used to override the default project detection from
SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation.

Explanation from Jaroslav Tulach:

[...] Historically the Graal project provided mx netbeansinit support
which generates 8.2 Ant nbproject/project.xml projects based on content
of suite/mx.suite/suite.py. They were usually located in
suite/src/*/nbproject directories.

To fix this, the idea is, not only to use the current MX project
detection (it requires a folder `mx.proj` to be found in the project
folder `proj`), but also look two level ups from the current directory.
If that directory is recognised as a MX project, that project will
be returned as the project for the requested directory.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KacerCZ/netbeans/commits/460042be723b28b430f88c77c1ee7ab18f364892"},{"sha":"5efb6e75212f4885fc76b27ab9e62171b3b317e6","author":{"name":"Jan Lahoda","email":"f0e6c8b88151cef643d02fd650fc0b650ee35a7f@netbeans.org"},"message":"Register JDKPlatformProvider when creating javac in ant's ClassLoader.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KacerCZ/netbeans/commits/5efb6e75212f4885fc76b27ab9e62171b3b317e6"},{"sha":"71b0379fd083d726d6a7fd207683dd1d2566d811","author":{"name":"Jan Lahoda","email":"f0e6c8b88151cef643d02fd650fc0b650ee35a7f@netbeans.org"},"message":"Adding test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KacerCZ/netbeans/commits/71b0379fd083d726d6a7fd207683dd1d2566d811"},{"sha":"78070a899ea99e1f0d65c7a4db6d9277bfdb1365","author":{"name":"Jaroslav Tulach","email":"872270679d6b683587ccc2f713e451b9fad3065f@oracle.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #2782 from MartinBalin/vscode/build_md_update

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Dynamism computation could fail if the input depends on some unsupported ops like custom-call. In such cases, all elements for the input should conservatively be marked as dynamic and not static.

This was already the case in TF1, but in TF2, InputSpec.dtype previously was checked both before and after the inputs were casted, requiring the input dtype before the cast and the compute dtype to match InputSpec.dtype. Now it's only checked before inputs are casted

This is in accordance with the RFC: https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20200929-keras-mixed-precision.md#inputspecs

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361012666
Change-Id: I8c9b3ff407d6b219924cc6d94e17376cf06d4dac","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/91a7a6e06755e59883bcb03af073770b869884eb"},{"sha":"c68bab85bb6702367f66fe13e228c1a582810ef0","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Have layers check InputSpec.dtype only before inputs are casted.

This was already the case in TF1, but in TF2, InputSpec.dtype previously was checked both before and after the inputs were casted, requiring the input dtype before the cast and the compute dtype to match InputSpec.dtype. Now it's only checked before inputs are casted

This is in accordance with the RFC: https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20200929-keras-mixed-precision.md#inputspecs

Change-Id: I8c9b3ff407d6b219924cc6d94e17376cf06d4dac","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/91a7a6e06755e59883bcb03af073770b869884eb"},{"sha":"c68bab85bb6702367f66fe13e228c1a582810ef0","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Have layers check InputSpec.dtype only before inputs are casted.

This was already the case in TF1, but in TF2, InputSpec.dtype previously was checked both before and after the inputs were casted, requiring the input dtype before the cast and the compute dtype to match InputSpec.dtype. Now it's only checked before inputs are casted

This is in accordance with the RFC: https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20200929-keras-mixed-precision.md#inputspecs

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Change-Id: Ib383fa360d9e80cddd3cdcae784bd0db75393d8c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/435c155dbed9c341f33d6cf46a1d3a9306f72934"},{"sha":"15d3f3dacc617ad88033bbf15de4be3387bf89cf","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass output sharding of all outputs to `MapClusterOutputIndexWithRegionOutputIndex`.

Output sharding of all prior outputs is required to correctly compute the mapping of cluster output and per core output. The previous logic of `GetTileShardedOutputsToMerge` and `HandleTileShardedOutputs` was not correct as it only passed the output sharding of one output.
This is exposed when one of the earlier outputs is placed on a single core ("MAXIMAL" sharding) and the latter output is split between cores ("OTHER" i.e., tiled sharding).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Change-Id: Ib383fa360d9e80cddd3cdcae784bd0db75393d8c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/435c155dbed9c341f33d6cf46a1d3a9306f72934"},{"sha":"15d3f3dacc617ad88033bbf15de4be3387bf89cf","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass output sharding of all outputs to `MapClusterOutputIndexWithRegionOutputIndex`.

Change-Id: I76f3f531102e9b361ba98b95bf54e8335689aafc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/e0a81a4ee7f475a9d189b56bf212187e9a7373c5"},{"sha":"d4dffb1c29ba27bb0859fe5547b00404069ffad4","author":{"name":"Mehdi Amini","email":"808100943be7b7010123d78912f654820a5ee1c1@google.com"},"message":"Introduce a `RefineTypeWith` method in shape_inference (NFC)

This method takes two TensorFlow types and tries to produce a more refined
type, where "refine" implies that more static information are known about
it.
This patch is NFC, the new method is introduced and correctness checked by
changing the implementation of `CanRefineTypeWith` to use this new method.
A future patch will refactor the uses of CanRefineTypeWith to use this in
more places directly, and in particular to improve our handling of
types with subtypes (resource and variant).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

[{"sha":"0029a3c377e9e0e05d6a381dda1ac418f4357e9f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Fix bug when LossScaleOptimizer and gradient_aggregator were used.

Before, if there were multiple processes each with a LossScaleOptimizer, and the inner optimizer had a custom gradient_aggregator to aggregate gradients across the processes, the LossScaleOptimizers in the processes could become out of sync. In particular, if a strict subset of replicas encountered NaN gradients, only the LossScaleOptimizers with NaN gradients would skip the step, while the LossScaleOptimizers with finite gradients would still apply gradients

Resolves https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/46863. Horovod was broken with LossScaleOptimizer in TF 2.4 due to this bug, but they patched in a workaround. With this fix, the workaround will not be necessary in TF 2.5.

The issue was caused by the fact the gradients were checked for NaNs before they were all-reduced. This was handled correctly with tf.distribute.Strategy but not with an arbitrary gradient_aggregator. Now, the gradients are all-reduced before they are checked for NaNs, which means if any replica has NaNs, they all will have NaNs.

This potentially will allow better performance in the future as well, as it allows earlier-computed gradients to be all-reduced in parallel with the computation of later-computed gradients.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Change-Id: Ib383fa360d9e80cddd3cdcae784bd0db75393d8c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/435c155dbed9c341f33d6cf46a1d3a9306f72934"},{"sha":"15d3f3dacc617ad88033bbf15de4be3387bf89cf","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass output sharding of all outputs to `MapClusterOutputIndexWithRegionOutputIndex`.

Output sharding of all prior outputs is required to correctly compute the mapping of cluster output and per core output. The previous logic of `GetTileShardedOutputsToMerge` and `HandleTileShardedOutputs` was not correct as it only passed the output sharding of one output.
This is exposed when one of the earlier outputs is placed on a single core ("MAXIMAL" sharding) and the latter output is split between cores ("OTHER" i.e., tiled sharding).

type, where "refine" implies that more static information are known about
it.

changing the implementation of `CanRefineTypeWith` to use this new method.

more places directly, and in particular to improve our handling of
types with subtypes (resource and variant).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Change-Id: Ib383fa360d9e80cddd3cdcae784bd0db75393d8c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/435c155dbed9c341f33d6cf46a1d3a9306f72934"},{"sha":"15d3f3dacc617ad88033bbf15de4be3387bf89cf","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass output sharding of all outputs to `MapClusterOutputIndexWithRegionOutputIndex`.

Output sharding of all prior outputs is required to correctly compute the mapping of cluster output and per core output. The previous logic of `GetTileShardedOutputsToMerge` and `HandleTileShardedOutputs` was not correct as it only passed the output sharding of one output.
This is exposed when one of the earlier outputs is placed on a single core ("MAXIMAL" sharding) and the latter output is split between cores ("OTHER" i.e., tiled sharding).

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Change-Id: Ib383fa360d9e80cddd3cdcae784bd0db75393d8c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/435c155dbed9c341f33d6cf46a1d3a9306f72934"},{"sha":"15d3f3dacc617ad88033bbf15de4be3387bf89cf","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass output sharding of all outputs to `MapClusterOutputIndexWithRegionOutputIndex`.

Output sharding of all prior outputs is required to correctly compute the mapping of cluster output and per core output. The previous logic of `GetTileShardedOutputsToMerge` and `HandleTileShardedOutputs` was not correct as it only passed the output sharding of one output.
This is exposed when one of the earlier outputs is placed on a single core ("MAXIMAL" sharding) and the latter output is split between cores ("OTHER" i.e., tiled sharding).

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

[{"sha":"40e15760e02d3c8afd145f385aae570813336893","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

[{"sha":"15d3f3dacc617ad88033bbf15de4be3387bf89cf","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass output sharding of all outputs to `MapClusterOutputIndexWithRegionOutputIndex`.

Output sharding of all prior outputs is required to correctly compute the mapping of cluster output and per core output. The previous logic of `GetTileShardedOutputsToMerge` and `HandleTileShardedOutputs` was not correct as it only passed the output sharding of one output.
This is exposed when one of the earlier outputs is placed on a single core ("MAXIMAL" sharding) and the latter output is split between cores ("OTHER" i.e., tiled sharding).

[{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

[{"sha":"7368fc8fe76b9c04ce0c622402908139ad2e740a","author":{"name":"Martin Balin","email":"84ffdecb1b029a3e0ae894af0e87a1e5e13ecda9@oracle.com"},"message":"Updates to better document the build of VSCode.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cenbe/netbeans/commits/7368fc8fe76b9c04ce0c622402908139ad2e740a"},{"sha":"460042be723b28b430f88c77c1ee7ab18f364892","author":{"name":"Matthias Bläsing","email":"2733b4844ad39354bd21fd2bca55a8804e19a60d@doppel-helix.eu"},"message":"[NETBEANS-5380] Override generated ant projects for MX with NetBeans support

In profiles from repositry updater runs a huge CPU load originating 
from SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl was found. In parallel excessive runtimes
for project scanning were observed.

Comparing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl and SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation
the latter has an aggressive caching system, which results in much less
cpu usage. Just removing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl is not a solution, as
it is used to override the default project detection from
SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation.

Explanation from Jaroslav Tulach:

[...] Historically the Graal project provided mx netbeansinit support
which generates 8.2 Ant nbproject/project.xml projects based on content
of suite/mx.suite/suite.py. They were usually located in
suite/src/*/nbproject directories.

To fix this, the idea is, not only to use the current MX project
detection (it requires a folder `mx.proj` to be found in the project
folder `proj`), but also look two level ups from the current directory.
If that directory is recognised as a MX project, that project will
be returned as the project for the requested directory.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cenbe/netbeans/commits/460042be723b28b430f88c77c1ee7ab18f364892"},{"sha":"5efb6e75212f4885fc76b27ab9e62171b3b317e6","author":{"name":"Jan Lahoda","email":"f0e6c8b88151cef643d02fd650fc0b650ee35a7f@netbeans.org"},"message":"Register JDKPlatformProvider when creating javac in ant's ClassLoader.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cenbe/netbeans/commits/5efb6e75212f4885fc76b27ab9e62171b3b317e6"},{"sha":"71b0379fd083d726d6a7fd207683dd1d2566d811","author":{"name":"Jan Lahoda","email":"f0e6c8b88151cef643d02fd650fc0b650ee35a7f@netbeans.org"},"message":"Adding test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cenbe/netbeans/commits/71b0379fd083d726d6a7fd207683dd1d2566d811"},{"sha":"78070a899ea99e1f0d65c7a4db6d9277bfdb1365","author":{"name":"Jaroslav Tulach","email":"872270679d6b683587ccc2f713e451b9fad3065f@oracle.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #2782 from MartinBalin/vscode/build_md_update

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Output sharding of all prior outputs is required to correctly compute the mapping of cluster output and per core output. The previous logic of `GetTileShardedOutputsToMerge` and `HandleTileShardedOutputs` was not correct as it only passed the output sharding of one output.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361193666
Change-Id: Id72546e7764b5fc8c992461df8d6f8f671057188","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/8933c05efb1a8346783b467219eb73053c38dc22"},{"sha":"99af36896cb6569179f34ba9a92922efe06d58de","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

When applying default values to collection types, null collections in
the input should result in empty collections in the output.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/178a9b32d7eee889e12d402ec066edbcdc0d96b6"},{"sha":"66f8d1c1c28bf729bd1b2b3919377ed9291f6080","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"functions: Fix defaults mismatched types fallback

We allow primitive fallback values which have mismatched types, but only
if there is a conversion to the target type. Previously we would allow
unsafe conversions (e.g. string to bool), but later had no capacity to
return an error if the conversion failed due to the value of the
fallback being unable to convert to the target type.

This commit makes the more conservative requirement that default
fallback values must have a safe conversion.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/66f8d1c1c28bf729bd1b2b3919377ed9291f6080"},{"sha":"98899df5147f8d0815d17445e2c4d10d6c87b415","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27979 from hashicorp/alisdair/defaults-fixes

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

We allow primitive fallback values which have mismatched types, but only
if there is a conversion to the target type. Previously we would allow
unsafe conversions (e.g. string to bool), but later had no capacity to
return an error if the conversion failed due to the value of the
fallback being unable to convert to the target type.

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361055208
Change-Id: Iaace4040aa94388965fb17e073c9caadc79d29b7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/d8d85aae446c90007250c466a9cb005d6d3f67bd"},{"sha":"40e15760e02d3c8afd145f385aae570813336893","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Note that the docstring of `Model.fit` is not updated yet because `DatasetCreator` is not exported as a public API yet. Once that's done, and `DatasetCreator` is supported with strategies other than `ParameterServerStrategy`, we should update the docstring to mention the additional supported type of `x`.

vendor containerd, BuildKit, protobuf, grpc, and golang.org/x","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/opensofttools/moby/commits/cc2d166cfd6185059c729173f33db13eeab00695"},{"sha":"ed033adb2cc287b513102e15fc47ddd60c51171d","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Builder: Check remote when local img platform doesn't match

This fixes an issue where if a build requests an image that already
exists in Docker's image store but does not match the specified build
platform, instead of building using the wrong platform go ahead and
check the remote for the correct platform.

Steps to reproduce issue:

```terminal
$ docker pull --platform=amd64 debian:buster
<output supressed>
$ cat Dockerfile
FROM debian:buster
RUN echo hello
$ docker build --platform=armhf -< Dockerfile
<output supressed>
```

Without this fix, the build invokcation will build using the amd64 image
since it is already tagged locally, but this is clearly not what we
want.

With the fix the local image is not used and instead we pull the correct
image.

This code was originally written for v1.10 migration where it signified that layers
were recomputed from pre 1.8 layout and could possibly change the tarball checksums.

It's now being repurposed in the BuildKit adapter but there it doesn't have any
warn condition as all data generated by builder is new anyway.

Currently, debug log entries as the one below may appear in the daemon logs:

   [2019-10-02T10:00:06.690674253Z] could not get checksum for "x128nsj79yzfx4j5h6em2w2on" with tar-split: "no tar-split file"

This patch removes the debug log, as it may confuse users ("we couldn't validate
what we downloaded, but we're gonna run it anyway?")

easy solution. Unfortunately when this code is in the hot path, it
becomes very expensive, so this commit changes some of those instances

Change-Id: Iaace4040aa94388965fb17e073c9caadc79d29b7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/d8d85aae446c90007250c466a9cb005d6d3f67bd"},{"sha":"078772e803c7befd06846a2d92a592e9c9f104bc","author":{"name":"Nat Jeffries","email":"2e09a75ee8475320aa1ac5230cf082097d8413be@gmail.com"},"message":"Address review comment","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/078772e803c7befd06846a2d92a592e9c9f104bc"},{"sha":"40e15760e02d3c8afd145f385aae570813336893","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.

Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Don't use log1p in erfinv

We computed:
w = -Log1p(-x*x)

When w is less than 5, we would then compute:
w = w - 2.5

Using Log1p seems like a great idea as compared to Log:
Log((1+x)*(1-x)) loses precision when x is smaller than an ulp of 1.0 while
Log1p(-x*x) will only lose precision when x is smaller than sqrt(tiny).

However, 2.5 is very far away from the result of Log1p which means that we will
not manage to keep any additional precision that Log1p provides over Log.

Switching to Log keeps the same amount of multiplies and introduces an fp add
and subtract. However, some implementations of Log1p are pretty expensive
relative to Log. Let's just use Log here.
